1248","1379":"1379","1279":"1279","1301":"1301","ABT 1299":"omkring 1299","1299":"1299","Wolveton, Dorset, England":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, England","Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1279–1305":"1279–1305","1248–1301":"1248–1301","1299–1379":"1299–1379","1305":"1305","1248":"1248","1379":"1379","1279":"1279","1301":"1301","ABT 1299":"circa 1299","1299":"1299","Wolveton, Dorset, England":"Dorset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, England","Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1279–1305":"1279–1305","1248–1301":"1248–1301","1299–1379":"1299–1379","1305":"1305","1248":"1248","1379":"1379","1279":"1279","1301":"1301","ABT 1299":"about 1299","1299":"1299","Wolveton, Dorset, England":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, England","Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jordan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, French (mainly Alsace and Haute-Savoie), Polish, Czech, and Slovenian; Spanish and Hungarian (<b>Jordán</b>): from the Christian personal name or nickname <i>Jordan</i>. This is taken from the name of the river Jordan (Hebrew <i>Yarden</i>, a derivative of <i>yarad</i> ‘to go down’, i.e. to the Dead Sea). At the time of the Crusades it was a common practice for crusaders and pilgrims to bring back flasks of water from the river in which John the Baptist had baptized people, including Christ himself, and to use it in the christening of their own children. As a result <i>Jordan</i> became quite a common personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Giordano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Rocco, Antonio, Pasquale, Carmine, Vito, Domenic, Gaetano, Giuseppe, Sal, Santo.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Giordano</i>, an equivalent of   Jordan  ."]},{"name":"Jourdan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Dominique, Gabrielle, Henri, Lucien, Pierre, Raoul, Yves.","English: variant of   Jordan  .","French (mainly southern): variant of   Jourdain  , a cognate of 2 below."]},{"name":"Jourdain","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Henri, Pierre, Fritz, Hans, Jacques, Rommel.","French, Breton (mainly Finistère), and West Indian (mainly Haiti, also Martinique and Dominican Republic): from the French personal name <i>Jourdain</i>, an equivalent of   Jordan  .","English (London, Derbyshire): French-influenced variant of   Jordan  ; compare 1 above."]},{"name":"Jordison","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire, Durham, and Northumberland): from a Middle English pet form, <i>Jordi</i>, of the male personal name   Jordan   + <i>-son</i>, or directly from a phonetic shortening of <i>Jordanson</i>."]},{"name":"Jorden","meanings":["English: variant of   Jordan  .","North German (mainly <b>Jörden</b>): probably a variant of   Jordan  . Compare   Yerden   and   Yerdon  ."]},{"name":"Judd","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Judde</i>, <i>Jutte</i>, a pet form of   Jordan  .","German: variant of   Jude  ."]},{"name":"Jorda","meanings":["Catalan (<b>Jordà</b>): from the personal name <i>Jordà</i> (see   Jordan  )."]},{"name":"Jerden","meanings":["English: from a variant of the personal name <i>Jurdon</i>, an old form of   Jordan  ."]},{"name":"Gordan","meanings":["German: variant of   Jordan  . The surname <i>Gordan</i> is very rare in Germany.","Irish (Wexford and Sligo): adopted as an Anglicized form of <b>Mag Mhuirneacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Muirneachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>muirneach</i> ‘lovable’."]},{"name":"Jordon","meanings":["English: variant of   Jordan  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Jordan was born in 1279, in Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with John Dunster de Mohun II. She died in 1305, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1279–1305":"1279–1305","1248–1301":"1248–1301","1299–1379":"1299–1379","1305":"1305","1248":"1248","1379":"1379","1279":"1279","1301"